==English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ri:m/

===Etymology 1===
Old English ''rēam''.

====Noun====
'''ream''' ''(uncountable – obsolete except in dialects)''
# the [[cream]] of milk
# a [[froth]] or [[scum]]

===Etymology 2===
From Old French [[raime]] (French [[rame]]), from Arabic [[رزمة]] ''rizma'' ‘bundle’.

====Noun====
[[Category:English nouns]]
'''ream'''  (''plural:'' [[reams]])
# (''United Kingdom English''): A bundle, package, or quantity of paper, usually consisting of twenty [[quire]]s or 480 sheets. Sometimes called a '''short ream'''
# (''United States English''): A package of paper containing 500 sheets.
# an abstract large amount of something
#:''I can't go - I still have '''reams''' of work left.''

===Etymology 3===
Unknown origin.

====Verb====
[[Category:English verbs]]
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|ream||}}
# to enarge a hole, especially using a [[reamer]]; to [[bore]] a hole wider.
# (''Slang'') vigorous sexual intercourse, especially [[anal]]
# (''Slang'') to yell at or berate
#:''My boss '''reamed''' me out for being late again this morning.''


==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*rauwma-''.  Cognate with Middle Low German [[rom|rōm]] (Dutch [[room]]), Old High German [[roum]] (German [[Rahm]]), Old Norse [[rjumi|rjúmi]] (Icelandic [[rjómi]], Norwegian [[rømme]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ræ:am/

===Noun===
'''rēam''' ''m''
# [[cream]]

